<h3>Metadata</h3>

 <ul class="nav nav-list help-list" id="faq-metadata">
    <li class="expandable">
        <a class="accordion-toggle" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#faq-metadata" href="#collapseM1">
            What is metadata?
        <i class="icon-chevron-right"></i></a>
        <div id="collapseM1" class="accordion-body collapse">
           <p>
           Metadata is information describing a resource or collection of resources contained within ScholarSphere. This includes descriptive information (about the actual content of the object and the persons or entities responsible for it); technical metadata (about the file format, preservation actions taken on the resources), and administrative metadata (use restrictions or other copyright and licensing information, etc.). 
           </p>
        </div> 
    </li>
    <li class="expandable">
        <a class="accordion-toggle" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#faq-metadata" href="#collapseM2">
            Why should I pay attention to creating metadata?
        <i class="icon-chevron-right"></i></a>
        <div id="collapseM2" class="accordion-body collapse">
            <p>
            Metadata allows users to discover your content through searching on a number of different aspects of it -- subject search, author/creator search, format search, etc. It also allows content contributors to track the content they or others have submitted, i.e. files related to a grant-funded project, or about a particular topic of interest. It also helps other researchers understand how they may use the digital materials. 
            </p>        
        </div> 
    </li>
    <li class="expandable">
        <a class="accordion-toggle" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#faq-metadata" href="#collapseM3">
            How is metadata created in ScholarSphere at the point of submission and ingest?
        <i class="icon-chevron-right"></i></a>
        <div id="collapseM3" class="accordion-body collapse">
            <p>
            Two ways: auto-generation by the system (dates uploaded or modified, file size, etc.) , and contribution of metadata content by users( subject or keywords, creator names, notes.)  Metadata can be added to materials already in ScholarSphere.
            </p>            
        </div> 
    </li>
</ul>

